The paper discusses motion planning algorithms for robotics, which falls under the category of robotics and control (cs.RO). The paper also discusses theoretical properties and practical performance, which suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The use of probabilistic methods and sampling sequences suggests a connection to control theory and systems (cs.SY). Finally, the numerical experiments mentioned in the paper suggest a possible connection to computer vision (cs.CV) for perception and sensing.
